33. 2⁰, Gal. v. 1, “Stand fast therefore in the liberty wherewith Christ hath made us free.”

Ans. This refers to freedom from the Mosaic Ceremonial Law, as appears by the whole Epistle, and the history in the Acts.

34. 3⁰, Col. ii. 16, “Let no man therefore judge you in meat, or in drink, &c.''

Ans. This refers to the errour of the Pharisees, who taught as doctrines the traditions of men (Matth. xv. 9), enjoining some things as necessary, without the authority of God, and forbidding others3 by their precepts, “Touoh not, taste not, handle not,” Col. ii. 21.
